# Multiple Catch Blocks

You can have multiple catch blocks for different exception types. PHP will match the first block that matches the exception type.

```php
try {
    // code
} catch (ValidationException $e) {
    echo "Validation error: " . $e->getMessage();
} catch (DatabaseException $e) {
    echo "Database error: " . $e->getMessage();
} catch (Exception $e) {
    // catch any other exception
    echo "General error: " . $e->getMessage();
}
```

Order matters: put more specific exceptions first, then general ones.

```php
<?php
class MathException extends Exception {}
class DivideByZeroException extends MathException {}

function divide($a, $b) {
    if ($b == 0) {
        throw new DivideByZeroException('Cannot divide by zero');
    }
    return $a / $b;
}

try {
    echo divide(10, 0);
} catch (DivideByZeroException $e) {
    echo "Math error: " . $e->getMessage();
} catch (MathException $e) {
    echo "Other math error: " . $e->getMessage();
} catch (Exception $e) {
    echo "General error: " . $e->getMessage();
}
?>
```
